Sub-Sahara Africa Stocks: Standard Chartered, Kenya Commercial

-- B y   C h r i s   K a y
-- 
2011-05-18T15:21:29Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-18/sub-sahara-africa-stocks-standard-chartered-kenya-commercial.html
The Ghana Stock Exchange Composite
Index climbed for the fifth day, rising 1.2 percent to 1,189.77
as of the 3 p.m. close in Accra, the highest level since at
least Jan. 4.  Kenya’s All-Share Index dropped 0.3 percent to 75.71 as of
the 3 p.m. close of trading in Nairobi. The Nigerian Stock
Exchange All-Share Index declined for a second day, losing 0.1
percent to 25,788.06 by the 2:30 p.m. close in Lagos, according
to an e-mail from the bourse. Mauritius’s SEMDEX Index fell for
the second day, slumping 0.5 percent to 2,100.65 by the 1:30
p.m. close in  Port Louis .  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan  Africa ,
excluding  South Africa . Stock symbols are in parentheses.  Kenya Commercial Bank Ltd. (KNCB)  , the country’s third-
biggest lender by market value, gained for the first day in
eight, rising 25 cents, or 1 percent, to 25 shillings, after it
reduced the number of people on its executive committee to seven
from 22, it said in an e-mailed statement yesterday.  Standard Chartered Bank Kenya Ltd. (SCBL)  , the East
African nation’s fourth-biggest lender by market value, climbed
for a second day, with shares adding 1 shilling, or 0.4 percent,
to 252 shillings, after profit in the three months through March
rose 14 percent to 1.64 billion shillings ($19 million).  To contact the reporter on this story:
